The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, February 03, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Feb. 2: Disinvestment ministry has decided to defer by a month the public issue for divesting the governments 10 per cent equity in Gail. It would now take place after the public placement of equity in ONGC in March. The decision was taken at a meeting of the top ministry officials with the merchant bankers and legal advisors this evening, sources associated with the divestment process said. They said Sebi had given all the clearances for the public issue for both the oil PSUs even though these do not fall under the purview of existing guidelines.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 2: The credit demand from companies to fund business expansion plans is expected to grow substantially in the next one year, said Reserve Bank of India deputy governor Rakesh Mohan. This is due to the upsurge in economic growth.																								 Bangalore, Feb. 2: Microsoft today announced the appointment of Ravi Venkatesan as chairman and general manager of Microsoft India. In this newly-created post, Venkatesan will have direct responsibility for Microsofts marketing, sales, operational and business development efforts in India, the company said.																								 New Delhi, Feb. 2: The Central Electricity Regulatory Commission today issued orders for inter-state transmission of power, prohibiting discrimination by state electricity boards. The move is aimed at introducing competition in power supply industry.
